### Final Verification

After all 6 tasks are complete, run the full verification suite:

**Step 1: Full unit tests**
Run: `zig build test 2>&1 | tail -30`
Expected: PASS — all modules compile and pass with the new error sets and API changes

**Step 2: TLS-specific tests**
Run: `zig build test-tls 2>&1 | tail -30`
Expected: PASS

**Step 3: Build check (no test, just compile)**
Run: `zig build`
Expected: Clean build — catches any remaining type mismatches from error set changes

**Step 4: Grep for stale references**
Run: `grep -rn 'tryEnableKtls\|extractKeyMaterial\|configureKtlsForDirection' serval-tls/ serval-server/ serval-client/ serval-socket/ --include='*.zig'` (exit code 1 = no matches = correct)
Expected: No hits. Note: `SSL_export_keying_material` is excluded from this check — the extern binding in ssl.zig is retained (it's a valid OpenSSL API, just no longer used for kTLS). Only the *callers* of that function were removed.

**Step 5: kTLS runtime integration test**

The core architectural change (native kTLS via BIO) must be verified at runtime, not just at compile time. Add a focused integration test to `serval-tls/stream.zig` (test section) that exercises the actual handshake path and validates the BIO check:

The unit test for kTLS should exercise a real handshake, not just check pre-handshake state. Add a loopback handshake test to `serval-tls/stream.zig` (test section) using the existing test cert infrastructure:

```zig
test "native kTLS BIO status after loopback handshake" {
    ssl.init();

    // Create server and client contexts with test certs
    const server_ctx = try ssl.createServerCtxFromPemFiles(
        "experiments/tls-poc/cert.pem",
        "experiments/tls-poc/key.pem",
    );
    defer ssl.SSL_CTX_free(server_ctx);

    const client_ctx = try ssl.createClientCtx();
    defer ssl.SSL_CTX_free(client_ctx);

    // Create socketpair for loopback
    const fds = try std.posix.socketpair(.{ .FAMILY = .LOCAL }, .{ .TYPE = .STREAM }, null);
    defer std.posix.close(fds[0]);
    defer std.posix.close(fds[1]);

    // Server side
    const server_ssl = ssl.SSL_new(server_ctx) orelse return error.SslNew;
    defer ssl.SSL_free(server_ssl);
    _ = ssl.SSL_set_options(server_ssl, ssl.SSL_OP_ENABLE_KTLS);
    if (ssl.SSL_set_fd(server_ssl, fds[0]) != 1) return error.SslSetFd;
    ssl.SSL_set_accept_state(server_ssl);

    // Client side
    const client_ssl = ssl.SSL_new(client_ctx) orelse return error.SslNew;
    defer ssl.SSL_free(client_ssl);
    ssl.SSL_set_verify(client_ssl, ssl.SSL_VERIFY_NONE, null);
    _ = ssl.SSL_set_options(client_ssl, ssl.SSL_OP_ENABLE_KTLS);
    if (ssl.SSL_set_fd(client_ssl, fds[1]) != 1) return error.SslSetFd;
    ssl.SSL_set_connect_state(client_ssl);

    // Drive handshake to completion with bounded alternating calls.
    // Socketpair is blocking, but handshake needs both sides to make progress.
    const max_handshake_rounds: u32 = 100;
    var rounds: u32 = 0;
    var client_done = false;
    var server_done = false;
    while (rounds < max_handshake_rounds and (!client_done or !server_done)) : (rounds += 1) {
        if (!client_done) {
            const rc = ssl.SSL_do_handshake(client_ssl);
            if (rc == 1) client_done = true
            else {
                const err = ssl.SSL_get_error(client_ssl, rc);
                if (err != ssl.SSL_ERROR_WANT_READ and err != ssl.SSL_ERROR_WANT_WRITE)
                    return error.HandshakeFailed;
            }
        }
        if (!server_done) {
            const rc = ssl.SSL_do_handshake(server_ssl);
            if (rc == 1) server_done = true
            else {
                const err = ssl.SSL_get_error(server_ssl, rc);
                if (err != ssl.SSL_ERROR_WANT_READ and err != ssl.SSL_ERROR_WANT_WRITE)
                    return error.HandshakeFailed;
            }
        }
    }
    if (!client_done or !server_done) return error.HandshakeFailed;

    // Check kTLS BIO status after handshake.
    const ktls_available = ktls.isKtlsRuntimeAvailable();
    const server_tx = if (ssl.SSL_get_wbio(server_ssl)) |wbio| ssl.BIO_get_ktls_send(wbio) else false;
    const server_rx = if (ssl.SSL_get_rbio(server_ssl)) |rbio| ssl.BIO_get_ktls_recv(rbio) else false;

    if (!ktls_available) {
        // Non-kTLS host: both must be false — this is the hard assertion.
        try std.testing.expect(!server_tx);
        try std.testing.expect(!server_rx);
    } else {
        // kTLS runtime is available (kernel module loaded), but native OpenSSL kTLS
        // may still not activate due to: BoringSSL linked, cipher not supported by
        // kernel kTLS, or OpenSSL build without kTLS support. Log result for
        // diagnostic visibility; do not assert true — that requires an environment
        // known to be fully kTLS-capable.
        log.info("kTLS test: runtime_available=true tx={} rx={}", .{ server_tx, server_rx });
    }
}
```

This test validates the critical path: real handshake → BIO check → result matches runtime capability.

Note: The socketpair handshake is blocking and both sides share a thread, so it may need a simple alternating-call loop if SSL_do_handshake returns WANT_READ. Adjust as needed during implementation — the key assertion is the BIO check result.

For full integration-level validation:
The `logKtlsStatus()` call after every handshake (stream.zig:169, 245) logs `ktls=enabled` or `ktls=disabled`. Capture integration output to verify:

```bash
zig build test-integration-tcp-runtime 2>&1 | tee /tmp/serval-ktls-test.log
# Check exit code separately — tee preserves it via PIPESTATUS
test ${PIPESTATUS[0]} -eq 0 || echo "FAIL: integration tests failed"
grep -q 'ktls=' /tmp/serval-ktls-test.log || echo "WARN: no kTLS log lines found"
```

Expected on kTLS-capable host: at least one `ktls=enabled`
Expected on non-kTLS host: all `ktls=disabled` (confirms graceful fallback)

For explicit disable test:
```bash
SERVAL_DISABLE_KTLS=1 zig build test-integration-tcp-runtime 2>&1 | tee /tmp/serval-ktls-disabled.log
test ${PIPESTATUS[0]} -eq 0 || echo "FAIL: integration tests failed"
# All lines must show disabled
grep 'ktls=enabled' /tmp/serval-ktls-disabled.log && echo "FAIL: kTLS enabled despite SERVAL_DISABLE_KTLS=1"
```
Expected: all `ktls=disabled`

