    const server_rx = if (ssl.SSL_get_rbio(server_ssl)) |rbio| ssl.BIO_get_ktls_recv(rbio) else false;

    // Invariant 1: TX and RX must agree (no partial-enable state).
    // This catches the original finding #2 regression on any host.
    try std.testing.expectEqual(server_tx, server_rx);

    // Invariant 2: on non-kTLS host, both must be false.
    if (!ktls_available) {
        try std.testing.expect(!server_tx);
    }

    // Invariant 3: if kTLS activated, the option bit must have been set.
    // (Sanity check — if BIO reports active but we didn't set the option, something is wrong.)
    if (server_tx) {
        try std.testing.expect(ktls_available);
    }
}
```

This test makes three hard assertions on every host:
- TX == RX (no partial enable — catches finding #2 regressions)
- Non-kTLS host → both false (fallback works)
- If kTLS active → runtime was available (causal consistency)

On a kTLS-capable host with OpenSSL 3.x, all three pass and `server_tx == true` proves the full critical path. On a non-kTLS host or BoringSSL, all three pass via the false path.

